{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1da20228-dc3b-446c-b593-e0303e60d435","content":"I don't see a `.dmp` file in the current directory. Could you provide the path to your crash dump file? In the meantime, here's a quick guide on how to analyze it:\n\n### Analyzing a .NET crash dump\n\n**Option 1: `dotnet-dump` (recommended for .NET apps)**\n```bash\n# Install the tool\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\n\n# Open the dump interactively\ndotnet-dump analyze /path/to/your/file.dmp\n```\n\nUseful commands inside the analyzer:\n| Command | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `clrstack` | Managed call stack of current thread |\n| `pe` (or `printexception`) | Print last exception details |\n| `dumpheap -stat` | Heap summary (for OOM issues) |\n| `threads` | List all threads |\n| `setthread <id>` | Switch to a specific thread |\n| `clrstack -all` | Stacks for all threads |\n\n**Option 2: `lldb` + SOS (Linux)**\n```bash\ndotnet-sos install\nlldb --core /path/to/your/file.dmp\n# then: clrstack, pe, etc.\n```\n\n**Option 3: WinDbg (Windows dumps)**\nUse WinDbg with the SOS debugging extension.\n\n---\n\nPlease share the path to your `.dmp` file and I can walk through the analysis with you.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b3ebabcd-12a4-4a9d-a481-c978ed141c85","outputTokens":342},"id":"41afdd90-8cfc-4db6-8df3-7213cc49eae3","timestamp":"2026-04-05T01:05:49.788Z","parentId":"eeca3057-cacb-44f2-ba81-0a0061df6c84"}
